f tourist sites. Borer shows how our interactions with the things we care about—and the ways that we care about how they’re made, treated, and consumed—can lead to new senses of belonging and connections with and to others and the places where we live.In a world where people and things move around at an extraordinary pace, the folks Borer spent time talking (and drinking) with remind us to slow down and learn how to taste the “good life,” or at least a semblance of it, even in a city where style is often valued over substance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aAesthetic ecology.  aAesthetics.  aConspicuous consumption.  aConsumption.  aCulture.  aEthnography.  aFestivals.  aGender.  aIdentity.  aImage.  aKnowledge.  aLocal.  aObjects.  aPhotography.  aPlace.  aReputation.  aSenses.  aSexism.  aSocial media.  aSocialization.  aStatus.  aTaste.  aTranslocal.  aTranslocalism.  aTrauma.  aUrban.  aVirtual scene.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479876181.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876181423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479876181/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles